# Pre-commit review checklist

This checklist captures recurring failure classes seen in agent-generated code:
partial edits, caller drift, weak tests, schema skew, error-path regressions,
misleading docs, and branch discipline failures.

## A. Before staging

0. **PR branch first.** Unless the user authorized direct default-branch work in
   this same request, run `bash scripts/git/assert-not-on-default-branch.sh`
   before `git add` or `git commit`. For a new scoped task, first run
   `bash scripts/git/prepare-work-branch.sh <topic-slug>`.
1. **Read the full local context.** For every edit, read the surrounding file,
   the caller, and the callee. Do not patch only the visible diff.
2. **Grep every caller.** If you renamed, retyped, restricted, loosened, moved,
   or repurposed a function, constant, type, route, component, env var, table,
   column, event, or permission, search the repo and verify every caller.
3. **Grep every writer.** If you change a field or state transition, find every
   other writer of the same fact and confirm there is one clear owner.
4. **Check repo profile.** If the repository is new to you, read or create
   `docs/agent/REPO_PROFILE.md` from the template before editing.

## B. Tests

5. **Tests must fail without the fix.** Mentally revert the fix. If the new test
   still passes, strengthen it.
6. **Order-sensitive behavior must assert order.** Do not rely on call counts
   when sequence, newest/oldest order, retry order, or event order matters.
7. **Run focused checks after meaningful edits.** Use the repo's real commands:
   lint, typecheck, unit tests, migration checks, build, or targeted tests. If
   commands are unknown, inspect `package.json`, `pyproject.toml`, `Makefile`,
   `Cargo.toml`, `go.mod`, CI workflows, and README files.
8. **Restore mutated globals.** Tests that patch globals, timers, DOM APIs,
   environment variables, module state, or process state must restore them in
   teardown.

## C. Async and state correctness

9. **One fact, one writer.** If two async paths update the same user-visible or
   persisted fact, define the winner and remove or gate the competing write.
10. **Side effect before promise row.** If a database row or status promises that
    a job, email, upload, webhook, notification, or external call exists, perform
    or enqueue the side effect before writing the row that claims it happened.
11. **Hydration cannot overwrite newer local intent.** URL params, sockets,
    polling, optimistic state, and callbacks must not reattach or overwrite after
    an intentional detach/cancel/reset.

## D. Error paths and logs

12. **Do not lose diagnostics.** If you narrow an error path or throw earlier,
    preserve the logging, metrics, trace IDs, and user-safe error surfaces relied
    on by operators.
13. **Do not reuse callbacks across severity.** Success/info/error/warning
    callbacks must remain semantically distinct.
14. **User-visible errors use shared extraction helpers.** If the repo has an API
    error unwrap helper, use it instead of generic `error.message` fallbacks.

## E. Schema, deploy skew, and migrations

15. **Code must tolerate not-yet-applied schema.** When code depends on a recent
    migration, handle missing columns, missing enum values, missing indexes,
    missing views, and old row shapes safely.
16. **Fallback writes mirror primary writes.** Degraded or compatibility paths
    must not silently skip fields written by the main path.
17. **Migration semantics matter.** Check transaction requirements, lock impact,
    reversibility, default values, backfills, view replacement rules, RLS policy
    order, and tenant ownership before shipping migrations.
18. **Health readiness reflects safety.** If the app can serve traffic without a
    required isolation, auth, migration, or data-integrity prerequisite, readiness
    must fail rather than report merely degraded.

## F. Event windows and capped collections

19. **Spread direction must match slice direction.** Newest-at-bottom uses
    `[...prev, item].slice(-N)`. Newest-at-top uses `[item, ...prev].slice(0, N)`.
20. **Boundary test at N+1.** Any capped buffer needs a test that inserts one
    more item than the cap and verifies exactly which item drops.

## G. Third-party APIs

21. **Verify contracts before calling.** Check official docs or installed types
    for argument order, lock behavior, retry semantics, IDs, pagination,
    idempotency, rate limits, date formats, webhooks, and error codes.
22. **Normalize input once.** External IDs, slugs, currency units, timestamps,
    files, and provider-specific variants should be normalized at the boundary.

## H. Docs and PR parity

23. **PR text must match the final patch.** Re-read the PR body and changed docs
    against the final diff before pushing.
24. **Screenshots and copy must reflect shipped behavior.** Do not claim an
    interaction, integration, performance, accessibility property, or external
    availability that was not implemented and verified.
25. **External claims require live verification when possible.** If the PR says a
    provider, model, package, API, price, domain, endpoint, or standard behaves a
    certain way, verify it against a current primary source.

## I. Domain policy and high-risk defaults

26. **Read binding domain policy before changing high-impact behavior.** This
    includes auth, billing, tenant isolation, model selection, safety filters,
    compliance, healthcare/legal/financial decisions, data retention, privacy,
    and irreversible actions.
27. **Do not mutate protected prompts, policies, prices, trust rules, or default
    providers casually.** Treat them as public contracts unless the task clearly
    authorizes the change.

## J. Resource cleanup and path hygiene

28. **Early returns clean up.** If normal flow deletes staged files, releases
    locks, rolls back jobs, closes handles, removes temp dirs, or updates status,
    every early return before that point must do the same.
29. **After file mutation, update every reference.** Variables, DB rows, logs,
    download links, backup jobs, upload calls, manifests, and return values must
    point to the new canonical path.
30. **Guard symmetry in sweeps.** If one sibling sweep path gets a new exemption,
    dry-run guard, retention check, or ownership condition, apply it to all
    siblings unless a doc explains the exception.

## K. UI tiering, permissions, and query safety

31. **Do not show restricted defaults while access is loading.** Use a loading
    state or permissive-until-known state; never flash a lower tier because the
    query has not resolved.
32. **Admin/owner overrides must be symmetric.** If one UI gate includes an admin
    bypass, matching backend routes and sibling UI gates must include equivalent
    logic.
33. **Set query `enabled` when UI is gated.** Do not fetch data for users who can
    never see the result.
34. **Reuse shared query keys intentionally.** Duplicate observers with different
    options can create racey cache behavior.

## L. Data ownership and isolation

35. **RLS and policy filters execute before route-level SQL.** Route predicates
    cannot recover rows hidden by database-level policy. Use migrations,
    backfills, or policy updates deliberately.
36. **Ownership can flow through multiple paths.** Enumerate all legitimate owner
    paths before adding a permission restriction.

## M. Runtime and environment parity

37. **Documented env vars must be honored by runtime clients.** If docs mention
    both `SERVICE_URL` and host/port pieces, validation and connection code must
    accept and use the same forms.
38. **Bootstrap-only secrets must not leak into app processes.** Admin URLs,
    superuser tokens, migration keys, and break-glass credentials must be scoped
    to the bootstrap subprocess and unset before runtime start/reload.

---

If a review finding surprises you and represents a repeatable class, extend the
closest rule. The rule layer is first-class project memory.
